ğŸ”¹ What is an Array?
â¡ï¸ An array is a collection of homogeneous (same type) elements stored in contiguous memory locations.
â¡ï¸ It allows storing multiple values under a single variable name, accessed using index.
`


ğŸ”¹ Key Features of Arrays:

â¡ï¸ Fixed Size: Size must be known at compile time.
â¡ï¸ Same Data Type: All elements must be of same type.
â¡ï¸ Index-based: Index starts from 0 to size - 1.
â¡ï¸ Stored in contiguous memory.
â¡ï¸ Faster access to elements using indices.




ğŸ”· Array Declaration and Memory Representation in C
ğŸ”¸ Declaration
int A[5] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
A[5] means an array of 5 integers.

Letâ€™s assume:
ğŸ“ Base Address = 1000
ğŸ“ Size of int = 4 bytes

ğŸ”¸ Address Calculation Formula
        Address of A[i]=Base Address + ğ‘– Ã— Size of Element

Where:
    i = index (starting from 0)
    Size of Element = 4 bytes (for int)
    Base Address = 1000

ğŸ”¸ Memory Address Table
ğŸ”¢ Index (i)	ğŸ”¸ Value	  ğŸ§® Address Calculation   	ğŸ“ Memory Address
